article.description:
Lauren Jackson scored 20 points, including a
crucial three-point play with 27 seconds remaining, and led the Seattle Storm to a 76-70 victory Monday night over the Indiana Fever.
article.headline: Storm solidify hold on second spot
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Badly outrebounded and outplayed for one
half, the Seattle Storm overcame an 11-point deficit in the second
to defeat the Indiana Fever 76-70 Monday night.

The Storm trailed by nine points at halftime after being
outrebounded 18-7 in the first half.

Lauren Jackson scored 20 points for Seattle, including a crucial
three-point play with 27 seconds remaining.

However, Seattle hit just one of its final nine shots in the
opening half to trail 39-30 at the break as the Fever capitalized
on an 18-7 advantage off the boards.

The Storm went more than six minutes without a field goal in the
first half. In the second half, Indiana went seven minutes without
a basket and the Storm rallied to record its franchise-best 19th
victory in the season.

"We just got focused. We're a good defensive team," Seattle
coach Anne Donovan said.

Seattle outrebounded Indiana 18-12 in the second half and put
the Fever without a field goal from the 17:03 mark until there was
9:28 to play. The Storm trailed 45-39 when Indiana's Deanna Jackson
hit a layup with 17:03 to play. Indiana didn't get another field
goal until the 9:28 mark that put the Fever ahead 52-51.

"We started out boxing out a little bit, and getting stops so
we could get our running game going," Donovan said. "They had
seven offensive rebounds in the first half to our one. We knew we
had to control the backboard."

Indiana had cut an eight-point deficit to two points on a layup
by Natalie Williams with 1:01 to go. Then, with time running out on
the shot clock, Betty Lennox put up a desperation shot from long
range that bounced away.

Jackson grabbed the rebound and hit a layup with 27 seconds
remaining. She also was fouled and hit the free throw.

Tamika Catchings, who led Indiana with 16 points, was called for
traveling as she attempted a drive on her team's next possession.
Jackson was fouled and hit one of two attempts to put Seattle up by
five with 22 seconds left, and the Fever never drew within four
points thereafter.

The Storm blocked a season-high 11 shots with reserve Janell
Burse recording five. Seattle also had a season-high 21 assists.

Sue Bird scored 17 points for Seattle (19-13), which solidified
its hold on the runner-up spot in the Western Conference. The Storm
lead third-place Minnesota by 1½ games with two to play and hold
the tiebreaker.

Bird had 15 of her points in the second half.

"We ran a lot of pick and rolls for her," Donovan said. " A
lot of screens. With Kelly (Miller) in foul trouble we wanted to
see if we could get her in further trouble. Indiana likes to switch
on that ball screen and we feel that's a great advantage for us."

Kelly Schumacher had 15 points, Natalie Williams 11, and Deanna
Jackson and Miller 10 apiece for the Fever.

Sherri Sam and Burse had 10 points each for the Storm, who
limited the Fever to 33 percent from the floor in the second half.

The loss was a serious one for Indiana (15-17). The Fever fell
into a tie for fifth place with Detroit in the East, where only 1½
games separate the last place team from coleaders Charlotte and
Connecticut.
